The UV–vis absorption spectra of Cy7-CH3 and CyCDs are shown in Fig. 2D, and the characteristic absorption band of Cy7-CH3 centered at 775 nm is the same as that of CyCDs. The dominant absorption (300–600 nm) revealed π–π* and n-π* transitions, which were attributed to the CC and CN/CO bonds of the aromatic rings, respectively. As shown in Fig. S3, the 1H NMR spectrum of CyCDs showed active hydrogen signals of aromatic hydrogen, and signals between 3.0 and 4.5 ppm may be due to the presence of oxygen-containing groups [40]. These results verify that the optical properties of cyanine dye were partially retained. The lifetime curve can be fitted with a double exponential function with two lifetimes of 0.56 ns (29.8%) and 2.24 ns (70.2%), thereby indicating the presence of different energy levels on the surface of CyCDs (Fig. S4) [34]. Upon excitation at different wavelengths, the CDs emitted near-infrared fluorescence at ∼804 nm and showed excitation-independent fluorescence emission, demonstrating that their fluorescence processes were dominated by uniform emissive states (Fig. S5) [4,5]. However, it should be noted that the CyCDs also present an obvious NIR-II emission (λem = 1160 nm) from 1100 to 1200 nm under 808 nm laser excitation (Fig. 2E). The absolute fluorescence quantum efficiency (Φf
                        ) of CyCDs was 15.3%, which is 8 times that of Cy7-CH3 (Φf
                         = 1.8%) in methanol, implying that the obtained CyCDs are promising fluorescent probes for NIR-I/NIR-II bioimaging.
